Using the RI Department of Health data, I will predict whether length of stay is longer or shorter than 4 days (the national average is 4.5 days). The 2016 and 2017 data will be used to predict for 2018.

The following chunk creates training data and testing data and selects variables that will be used for modeling. These are variables that would be know initially when the patient comes in. For example, none of the total charge variables should be included as they would not be known until the end of the patient’s stay.

DATA3 <- DATA2 %>% 
  group_by(dx1) %>% 
  mutate(freq_dx1 = n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(dx2) %>% 
  mutate(freq_dx2 = n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(los_ind = factor(ifelse(los >= 4, 1, 0)),
         quant_dx1 = ntile(freq_dx1, 4),
         quant_dx2 = ntile(freq_dx2, 4)) %>%
  mutate_at(vars(asource, dx1, dx2), as.character) %>% 
  select(los_ind, age, pay_ub92, sex, raceethn, provider, moa, 
         admtype, service, quant_dx1, quant_dx2, yoa, payer) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  sample_n(10000)

set.seed(2020)

split <- createDataPartition(DATA3$los_ind, p = 0.7, list = F)
training <- DATA3[split,]
testing <- DATA3[-split,]

Decision Tree

mod1 <- train(los_ind ~ ., data = training, method = "rpart2",
              tuneGrid = expand.grid(maxdepth = c(3, 7, 12)),
              trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10))

mod1.pred <- predict(mod1, testing)
mod1.cm <- confusionMatrix(mod1.pred, testing$los_ind, positive = "1")
